  "answer": "**The term \"tehzib\" (often transliterated as تهذیب in Urdu/Arabic script, meaning refinement, civilization, or culture) does not appear in the English translations of Allama Iqbal's works available in the Falsafa corpus.** \n\nIqbal's contributions here are limited to the three parts of his Urdu poetry collection *Bang-e-Dara* (1924), which explore themes like Islamic renaissance, self-realization (*khudi*), and spiritual awakening.[^1][^2][^3] Searches for \"tehzib\" and common variants (\"tahzib\", \"tazhib\", \"tahdhib\", \"tehzeeb\", \"tahzeeb\"), as well as related English concepts like \"civilization Iqbal\" or \"culture Iqbal\", yielded zero results in the English bodies.\n\nNo critical function or definition of \"tehzib\" is present. Iqbal's prose works (e.g., *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam*)—where he might discuss cultural or civilizational themes more explicitly—are not in this corpus of 37 works.\n\n[^1]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, metadata from corpus listing.  \n[^2]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, metadata from corpus listing.  \n[^3]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, metadata from corpus listing.",
